MCQs: WordPress Plugin Supply Chain + ENS Abuse
1. What type of vulnerability best describes CVE-2026-6443?

A. SQL injection in WordPress core
B. Cross-site scripting in WooCommerce checkout
C. Embedded malicious code in a WordPress plugin supply chain
D. Authentication bypass in the WordPress admin panel

Answer: C

2. Why are WordPress ecommerce sites attractive targets for plugin supply-chain attacks?

A. WordPress does not support HTTPS
B. Ecommerce sites often rely on many third-party plugins with privileged application access
C. WordPress plugins cannot be updated
D. Ecommerce sites do not use databases

Answer: B

3. In the demo scenario, why is a filename like wp-comments-posts.php suspicious?

A. WordPress blocks all PHP files with “comments” in the name
B. It resembles the legitimate WordPress file wp-comments-post.php but includes a subtle extra “s”
C. It is a known Linux kernel file
D. It is always created by WooCommerce

Answer: B

4. What is the main purpose of a PHP webshell on a compromised WordPress server?

A. To improve website performance
B. To encrypt database backups
C. To allow remote command execution or attacker-controlled access
D. To validate SSL certificates

Answer: C

5. Why is modifying wp-config.php dangerous?

A. It only affects website styling
B. It is loaded during WordPress execution and contains sensitive configuration
C. It is used only for image uploads
D. It automatically disables all plugins

Answer: B

6. Which of the following is the most accurate description of traditional DNS from a takedown perspective?

A. DNS is fully decentralised and cannot be disrupted
B. DNS has centralised control points such as registrars, registries, and DNS providers
C. DNS does not support domain suspension
D. DNS only works inside local networks

Answer: B

7. What problem does ENS potentially solve for an attacker?

A. It hides malware from antivirus completely
B. It allows the attacker to use blockchain-based name resolution instead of relying only on traditional DNS
C. It prevents the victim machine from making network connections
D. It removes the need for persistence

Answer: B

8. In ENS resolution, what is the role of the ENS Registry?

A. It stores all website HTML files
B. It maps a namehash to ownership, resolver, and TTL information
C. It encrypts all Ethereum transactions
D. It scans domains for malware

Answer: B

9. What does the ENS Resolver usually do?

A. It stores or returns records associated with an ENS name
B. It deletes malicious smart contracts
C. It blocks DNS queries
D. It performs WordPress authentication

Answer: A

10. What cryptographic hash function is commonly associated with Ethereum namehash computation?

A. MD5
B. SHA-1
C. Keccak-256
D. bcrypt

Answer: C

11. What is the correct term for the protocol commonly used to query Ethereum nodes?

A. SMTP over TLS
B. Ethereum JSON-RPC, often over HTTPS
C. FTP over SSH
D. DNSSEC over UDP

Answer: B

12. Why can ENS-based resolution make detection harder for defenders?

A. It prevents all logs from being created
B. The victim may connect to an Ethereum RPC provider rather than making a direct DNS lookup for the attacker’s C2 domain
C. It disables endpoint monitoring
D. It only works on air-gapped systems

Answer: B

13. Which statement about HTTPS-based Ethereum JSON-RPC is most accurate?

A. HTTPS means nobody can see anything, including the RPC provider
B. HTTPS encrypts traffic in transit, but the RPC provider can still see the JSON-RPC request
C. HTTPS prevents DNS resolution from ever occurring
D. HTTPS makes malware impossible to detect

Answer: B

14. Which JSON-RPC method might be suspicious if repeatedly observed from a WordPress server process?

A. eth_call
B. mail_send
C. wp_login
D. dns_lookup

Answer: A

15. Which host-level detection would be most relevant for the WordPress side of this attack?

A. Monitoring for new or modified PHP files in WordPress directories
B. Monitoring GPU temperature
C. Detecting Bluetooth pairing attempts
D. Checking browser bookmarks

Answer: A

16. Which file integrity event should be treated as high priority on a WordPress server?

A. A new .jpg image uploaded by an editor
B. A new suspicious PHP file appearing in the WordPress root directory
C. A CSS colour change in a theme file
D. A normal log rotation event

Answer: B

17. Which PHP function pattern is commonly suspicious in webshells or malicious plugin code?

A. strlen()
B. array_merge()
C. eval(base64_decode(...))
D. date()

Answer: C

18. Why is detection based only on Keccak/namehash signatures insufficient?

A. Keccak is never used by attackers
B. Attackers can obfuscate, reimplement, or outsource the hashing logic
C. Keccak only works in Windows environments
D. Namehash detection only works on DNS logs

Answer: B

19. Which network indicator may suggest ENS or Ethereum RPC abuse from a compromised web server?

A. Outbound HTTPS traffic from PHP/Apache/Nginx worker processes to Ethereum RPC providers
B. Inbound SSH from an administrator
C. DNS queries to the company’s own domain
D. Internal NTP traffic

Answer: A

20. Which of the following is the best layered mitigation strategy?

A. Only block one suspicious IP address
B. Disable HTTPS
C. Combine plugin supply-chain controls, file integrity monitoring, PHP behaviour detection, and outbound RPC monitoring
D. Ignore plugin updates permanently

Answer: C

21. What is the main security lesson from the malicious plugin scenario?

A. Open-source software is always unsafe
B. Plugin trust and update provenance are critical parts of application security
C. DNS cannot be monitored
D. WordPress cannot be used securely

Answer: B

22. Why should the wp-config.php modification be described carefully in a presentation?

A. Because wp-config.php does not exist in WordPress
B. Because it may be part of the lab emulation rather than confirmed CVE behaviour
C. Because modifying it improves WordPress security
D. Because it only affects frontend CSS

Answer: B

23. What is the safest way to present the webshell and ENS beacon flow?

A. As confirmed behaviour of every affected plugin
B. As an adversary-emulation extension built from the supply-chain compromise scenario
C. As a DNS vulnerability
D. As a browser-only attack

Answer: B

24. Which of these is the most precise statement?

A. ENS makes C2 impossible to detect
B. ENS removes all need for internet access
C. ENS can act as a decentralised indirection layer for attacker infrastructure
D. ENS only works with email servers

Answer: C

25. Which detection source would best reveal suspicious changes to wp-config.php?

A. File integrity monitoring
B. GPU telemetry
C. DHCP lease logs only
D. Keyboard input logs

Answer: A

26. Which control helps reduce the risk of malicious WordPress plugin updates?

A. Install plugins from random ZIP files
B. Disable all logging
C. Use plugin allowlisting, update review, and trusted-source validation
D. Give all plugins write access to the filesystem

Answer: C

27. What is the difference between DNS-based C2 and ENS-assisted C2?

A. DNS-based C2 uses only Bluetooth
B. ENS-assisted C2 can retrieve attacker-controlled resolution data from blockchain smart contracts
C. ENS-assisted C2 cannot use HTTPS
D. DNS-based C2 does not require networking

Answer: B

28. What should defenders inspect when looking for Ethereum RPC abuse?

A. Destination domains, SNI, Host headers, User-Agent strings, and JSON-RPC methods
B. Only screen resolution
C. Only keyboard language
D. Only printer logs

Answer: A

29. Which statement about blocking Ethereum RPC providers is most accurate?

A. It is a useful control but can cause false positives and may be bypassed by using alternative providers
B. It guarantees full remediation
C. It deletes the attacker’s smart contract
D. It prevents all HTTPS traffic

Answer: A

30. What is the strongest conclusion from this attack chain?

A. ENS is malicious by design
B. WordPress is always insecure
C. Modern C2 detection must include application, endpoint, network, and decentralised-infrastructure visibility
D. DNS monitoring is no longer useful

Answer: C
